'''Girls' Generation''' (Hangul: <U+C18C><U+B140> <U+C2DC><U+B300>; Japanese: <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3>, also known as '''SNSD''' or '''So Nyeo Shi Dae''') is a South Korean [[girl group]] formed by [[S.M. Entertainment]] in 2007.<ref name="official profile">{{cite web|title=Girls' Generation Profile|url=http://girlsgeneration.smtown.com/Profile|publisher=SM Entertainment|accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> The nine-member group consists of [[Kim Tae-yeon|Taeyeon]], [[Jessica Jung|Jessica]], [[Sunny (singer)|Sunny]], [[Tiffany (South Korean singer)|Tiffany]], [[Kim Hyo-yeon|Hyoyeon]], [[Kwon Yuri|Yuri]], [[Sooyoung]], [[Im Yoona|Yoona]] and [[Seohyun]].

The group gained attention at the beginning of their career with songs such as "[[Into the New World (song)|Into the New World]]" and "[[Kissing You (Girls' Generation song)|Kissing You]]" but it was not until 2009 when they gained significant popularity with their hit single "[[Gee (Girls' Generation song)|Gee]]", which was classified by the online music store [[melon (online music service)|MelOn]] as the most popular song of the decade in South Korea (ranking based on chart performance).<ref>{{cite web|title=2000<U+B144><U+B300> <U+C74C><U+C545><U+C758> <U+D750><U+B984>|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110503062457/http://www.melon.com/svc/static_html/melonchart/age_chart_search.jsp?chartType=AG&chartDate=2000&classCd=KPOP|url=http://www.melon.com/svc/static_html/melonchart/age_chart_search.jsp?chartType=AG&chartDate=2000&classCd=KPOP|year=2011|accessdate=January 18, 2014|archivedate=May 3, 2011|language=Korean}}</ref> The group solidified their place in the Korean music industry with follow-up singles "[[Tell Me Your Wish (Genie) (song)|Tell Me Your Wish]]", "[[Run Devil Run (Girls' Generation song)|Run Devil Run]]", and "[[Oh! (Girls' Generation song)|Oh!]]" from late 2009 to early 2010. In 2011, after a series of activities in Japan, the group returned to the Korean music scene with "[[The Boys (Girls' Generation song)|The Boys]]", which was released in three languages: Korean, Japanese, and for the first time, English. In 2010 alone, the group sold more than 11,730,000 digital albums and singles collectively.<ref name="forbes11" /> The group's immense popularity in their native South Korea has earned them titles "The Nation's Singers" and "The Nation's Girl Group".<ref name="2010<U+B144> <U+C62C><U+D574><U+C758> 10<U+B300> <U+AC00><U+C218><U+C640> <U+AC00><U+C694>">{{cite web|url=http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=228&pagePos=1&selectYear=&search=&searchKeyword=|title=2010<U+B144> <U+C62C><U+D574><U+C758> 10<U+B300> <U+AC00><U+C218><U+C640> <U+AC00><U+C694>|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=November 25, 2012|publisher=Gallup Korea|language=Korea}}</ref> The ''Sisa'' Journal named the group as the most influential entertainers for the years 2011 and 2012, making them the first female idol group in history to make the list.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} They have also been listed as #1 on the Top Female Singer's list for four consecutive years on the Leespiar Popularity Survey in Korea.<ref>{{cite news|title=<U+C7A5><U+B3D9><U+AC74> <U+AE40><U+D0DC><U+D76C>, <U+D558><U+BC18><U+AE30> <U+AC00><U+C7A5> <U+C778><U+AE30><U+C788><U+B294> <U+B0A8><U+B140> <U+BC30><U+C6B0>|url=http://www.metroseoul.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=201747|accessdate=January 22, 2013|newspaper=Metro Seoul|date=October 23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2012 <U+D558><U+BC18><U+AE30> <U+C778><U+AE30><U+B3C4>, <U+C544><U+C774><U+C720> <U+C81C><U+CE5C> <U+5973><U+AC00><U+C218> 1<U+C704><U+B294>?|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/news/sk_index.html?cat=view&art_id=201210241730143&sec_id=540101&pt=nv|accessdate=January 22, 2013|newspaper=Sports Khan|date=October 24, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Asia Today]]'' placed the group at forty-four on the 50 Korean Power Leaders list in 2011.<ref name="<U+C544><U+C2DC><U+C544><U+D22C><U+B370><U+C774> <U+C120><U+C815>...<U+D55C><U+AD6D><U+C758> <U+D30C><U+C6CC><U+B9AC><U+B354> 50<U+C778>">{{ko icon}} [http://www.asiatoday.co.kr/news/view.asp?seq=434747 <U+C544><U+C2DC><U+C544><U+D22C><U+B370><U+C774> <U+C120><U+C815>...<U+D55C><U+AD6D><U+C758> <U+D30C><U+C6CC><U+B9AC><U+B354> 50<U+C778>] ''Asia Today''. December 31, 2010.</ref> The group also topped [[Forbes]]'s [[Korea Power Celebrity 40]] list for the years of 2010, 2011 and 2013.<ref name="forbes11">{{cite web|url=http://magazine.joinsmsn.com/forbes/article_view.asp?aid=287494#|title=Korea Power Celebrity 40|language=Korean|author=Son Yong|publisher=magazine.joinsmsn.com/forbes|date=February 24, 2011|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>

The group began a foray into the Japanese music scene in late 2010 under [[Universal Music Group|Nayutawave Records]], with Japanese remakes of their 2009 Korean hits "Genie" and "Gee". The group's debut Japanese album, ''[[Girls' Generation (2011 album)|Girls' Generation]]'', released in June 2011, is currently the highest selling album in Japan by a Korean group in [[Oricon]] history. It was certified "Million" by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]], which made them the second Korean artist to earn such an achievement in Japan since label mate [[BoA]]'s ''"Best of Soul"'' in 2005.<ref name="asahi.com">[http://www.asahi.com/ <U+671D><U+65E5><U+65B0><U+805E><U+30C7><U+30B8><U+30BF><U+30EB><U+FF1A><U+671D><U+65E5><U+65B0><U+805E><U+793E><U+306E><U+30CB><U+30E5><U+30FC><U+30B9><U+30B5><U+30A4><U+30C8><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

They have expanded their reach in the Korean industry through their first sub-unit, [[Girls' Generation-TTS]], composed of members Taeyeon, Tiffany, and Seohyun. The sub-unit debuted on 2012 with their mini album [[Twinkle (EP)|Twinkle]] which became the highest charting K-Pop act on the Billboard 200<U+2014>at No. 126 on Billboard 200.<ref>{{cite news|title=Girls' Generation Splinter Group Enters Billboard 200|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/489102/girls-generation-splinter-group-enters-billboard-200|accessdate=February 16, 2014|newspaper=Billboard}}</ref>

==Name==
In Korea, the group is referred to as '''So Nyeo Shi Dae''' ({{lang-ko|<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>}}). They are also referred to as '''SoShi''' ({{lang|ko|<U+C18C><U+C2DC>}}) or '''SNSD''', both abbreviated forms of the group's Korean name. The name Girls' Generation means that "The generation of girls<U+2019> domination has come."<ref>{{cite news|title=(Korean) <U+AC78><U+ADF8><U+B8F9> <U+C774><U+B984> <U+B73B>, <U+C228><U+ACA8><U+C9C4> <U+C758><U+BBF8><U+C5D0> <U+2018><U+ADF8><U+B807><U+AD6C><U+B098><U+2019>|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20120415n00436?mid=e0101|accessdate=February 23, 2013|newspaper=Nate|date=April 15, 2012}}</ref> The group is referred to as '''Shojo Jidai''' ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]; <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3>) or '''SJJD''' in Japan.<ref name="JapaneseName">{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2012/09/02/national/will-the-takeshima-dispute-break-the-korean-wave/#.UVj-Sb9RpfQ|title=Will the Takeshima dispute break the Korean wave?|author=Mark Schreiber|date=September 2, 2012|accessdate=April 1, 2013|publisher=japantimes.co.jp}}</ref>

==History==

===Pre-debut===
After the success of [[S.M. Entertainment]]'s boy band, [[Super Junior]], the company planned to debut a new girl group, which would ultimately turn into Girls' Generation, featuring a start-up roster of 11 members.<ref name="pre-debut history">[http://snsdkorean.com/2010/01/02/the-making-of-so-nyuh-shi-dae/ The Making of So Nyuh Shi Dae <U+00AB> SNSD Korean<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For nearly two years, Korean websites speculated about which of the female SM Entertainment trainees would be placed into the group. The candidate members were professionally trained primarily in singing and dancing, while some were also selected to be trained in acting and modeling. Many of the candidate members had participated in the Korean entertainment industry through their participation in magazine advertisements, television commercials, and small television drama or film appearances,{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} and Sooyoung even debuted in the Japanese market in 2002 as part of the pop duo, Route <U+03B8>, which soon disbanded in one year.<ref name="route0 profile">{{ja icon}} [http://www.randc.jp/route0/profile.html Route {{theta}} <U+2013> official website <U+2013> profile]</ref><ref>[http://www.musicasia.net/sooyoung-choi-sooyoung Sooyoung <U+2013> Choi Sooyoung | Music Asia | Singer <U+2013> Asia Music Portal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The group witnessed several revisions, as members were either added or cut, until final line-up of the debuting nine was decided. Prior to their announcement, it was rumored that the group would be named "Super Girls" after their so-called male counterparts, Super Junior.<ref name="pre-debut history" />

The first member of the group to join SM Entertainment's training system was Jessica in 2000, after she and her sister, [[Krystal (singer)|Krystal Jung]] (now a member of the girl group [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]]), were scouted in a mall in Korea during a family vacation.<ref>{{ko icon}} Chosun.com: [http://choen.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/02/18/2009021800465.html <U+C81C><U+C2DC><U+CE74>, "<U+AD00><U+AC1D> <U+C55E><U+C5D0><U+C11C><U+C758> <U+C81C> <U+BAA9><U+C18C><U+B9AC><U+C5D0> <U+AC10><U+B3D9><U+D588><U+C5B4><U+C694>"], February 18, 2009</ref> Also in 2000, members Sooyoung and Hyoyeon were cast into SM's training system through the 2000 SM Open Audition, in which Hyoyeon danced for her audition.<ref name=iam/> Yuri was the next Girls' Generation member to be accepted into SM's training system after finishing second in the ''2001 SM Youth Best Dancer'' competition. Yoona was cast the following year after auditioning singing and dancing to her favorite singers, [[BoA]] and [[Britney Spears]], in 2002 SM Saturday Open Casting Audition.<ref name=iam>{{cite AV media | people = SM Artists | title = I AM: SMTOWN LIVE WORLD TOUR in Madison Square Garden | medium = Blu-Ray | publisher = SM Town | location = New York, U.S. | date = 2012 | url = http://www.yesasia.com/global/i-am-smtown-live-world-tour-in-madison-square-garden-blu-ray-us-version/1031415754-0-0-0-en/info.html}}</ref> Seohyun, the group's youngest member, was scouted in the subway by an SM scout, then auditioned in 2003, singing children's songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/08/seohyun-sulli-krystal-and-taemins-audition-clips-revealed|title=Seohyun, Sulli, Krystal and Taemin<U+2019>s audition clips revealed|date=August 1, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2012|publisher=allkpop.com}}</ref> The group's leader, Taeyeon, was cast in 2004 after being discovered at SM's ''8th Annual Best Contest'' winning "Best Singer 1st Place & Grand Award".<ref name="The Musical report">{{ko icon}} [http://www.themusical.co.kr/magazine/magzine_sub_090526.aspx?part=12&num=16918 <U+C18C><U+B140>, <U+C790><U+C720><U+B97C> <U+AFC8><U+AFB8><U+B2E4>, <<U+D0DC><U+C591><U+C758> <U+B178><U+B798>><U+C758> <U+AE40><U+D0DC><U+C5F0> (No.80)], ''The Musical''. May 11, 2010. Retrieved May 15, 2010</ref> That same year, member Tiffany auditioned at SM's Starlight Casting System in Los Angeles, and joined the company in October 2004.<ref>{{ko icon}} Newsen.com: [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200708011017271002 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+D2F0><U+D30C><U+B2C8> "LA <U+CD95><U+C81C><U+C11C> <U+CE90><U+C2A4><U+D305>"], August 1, 2007</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} Chosun.com: [http://choen.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/02/13/2009021301267.html <U+D640><U+B85C> <U+C219><U+C18C> <U+C9C0><U+D0A4><U+B294> <U+D2F0><U+D30C><U+B2C8> "<U+C774><U+C81C><U+C11C><U+C57C> <U+C678><U+B85C><U+C6C0><U+C774> <U+BAB0><U+B824><U+C640><U+C694>"]. February 13, 2009</ref> The ninth and final member of the group to be added was Sunny, who entered the system in 1998, training for five years before transferring to another company, Starworld, where she trained to debut in the duo "Sugar", which ultimately never debuted. Then, under the recommendation of the singer Ayumi, she re-transferred back to SM Entertainment in 2007.<ref name="Sugar">{{ko icon}} [http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2007113015350222567&nvr= <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+C368><U+B2C8> SM <U+C774><U+C218><U+B9CC> <U+CE5C><U+C870><U+CE74> <U+2018><U+C288><U+AC00> <U+D6C4><U+C18D> <U+ADF8><U+B8F9> <U+BA64><U+BC84> <U+B420> <U+BED4><U+2019>]. asiae.co.kr. November 30, 2007. Retrieved June 15, 2010.</ref> Sunny is also the niece of S.M. Entertainment's founder, [[Lee Soo-man]].<ref>[http://www.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/view/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0000779709 '<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>' <U+C368><U+B2C8><U+B294> <U+C774><U+C218><U+B9CC><U+C758> <U+C870><U+CE74>...<U+C544><U+BC84><U+C9C0><U+B3C4> <U+AC00><U+C218> <U+CD9C><U+C2E0> <U+2013> <U+C624><U+B9C8><U+C774><U+B274><U+C2A4><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===2007<U+2013>2008: Debut and ''Girls' Generation''===
In July 2007, Girls' Generation had their unofficial first stage performance on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''School of Rock'' where the group performed their first single, "[[Into the New World (song)|Into the New World]]" ({{lang|ko|<U+B2E4><U+C2DC> <U+B9CC><U+B09C> <U+C138><U+ACC4>}}).
A documentary recording the story of the group's debut titled ''[[Girls' Generation Goes to School]]'' was filmed by Mnet during this time, revolving around their unofficial debut and first public performances through ''School of Rock''.
[[File:Girls Generation in BKK.jpg|thumb|left|Girls' Generation in February 2008 performing at [[Rajamangala Stadium]] in Bangkok, Thailand]]

The group's first single was physically released soon after, including an instrumental of the group's debut song and two other tracks: "Beginning" and "Perfect for You." The latter's Korean title is "Wish" ({{lang|ko|<U+C18C><U+C6D0>}}), which later became the name of Girls' Generation's official [[fan club]], S<U+2661>NE. The group's debut officially began on August 5, 2007, first performing on SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'', later on MBC ''[[Show! Music Core]]'' and KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]''. "Into the New World" achieved No.1 spot on Mnet ''[[M! Countdown]]''. The group released their [[Girls' Generation (2007 album)|first self-titled full album]] in late autumn of 2007 with the lead single "Girls' Generation" ({{lang|ko|<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>}}), a remake of [[Lee Seung-Cheol|Lee Seung-cheol]]'s 1989 song. Promotion for the single started in early November. The album also included the group's first single "[[Into the New World (song)|Into the New World]]", "Perfect For You" (re-titled "Honey"), and eight other tracks by the group. The group first album has sold more than 100,000 copies. The last pop-oriented girl group in Korea to accomplish this feat was [[S.E.S. (band)|S.E.S.]]<ref>{{cite news|title=^ (Korean)'<U+AC78> <U+B304><U+C2A4><U+ADF8><U+B8F9>', SES <U+C774><U+D6C4> 6<U+B144><U+B9CC><U+C5D0> '10<U+B9CC><U+C7A5> <U+C2DC><U+B300>'|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2008041516250673400&type=1|accessdate=December 25, 2012|newspaper=StarNews|date=April 15, 2012}}</ref>

In early 2008, Girls' Generation began promoting their second single from the album, "[[Kissing You (Girls' Generation song)|Kissing You]]", which won the group their first K-chart win after achieving the number-one position on the KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' February chart.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://bbs1tv.media.daum.net/gaia/do/talk/photophoto/read?bbsId=A000004&articleId=312951 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, '<U+B300><U+C131><U+D1B5><U+ACE1>'<U+C740> <U+D1B5><U+C0AC><U+ACE0> <U+B54C><U+BB38>? (Girls' Generation in a Car Accident Before Music Bank)]</ref> This song achieved the #1 spot on three major TV music rankings<U+2014>SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'', M.net M.Countdown! and ''Music Bank''. In March 2008, the album was repackaged, re-released and re-titled ''Baby Baby''. Girls' Generation released the teaser for their single "Baby Baby" on March 15, 2008. The single was released on digital music sites on March 17, 2008. The single, "Baby Baby", was released to promote the album. The group also performed "Baby Baby" on various music shows such as MBC ''[[Show! Music Core]]'', SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'', and Mnet ''[[M! Countdown]]'' in March and April. The album promotions was concluded on April 13, 2008, on ''Inkigayo''.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200804131525261002 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> 1<U+C9D1> <U+D65C><U+B3D9> <U+ACF5><U+C2DD> <U+B9C8><U+BB34><U+B9AC> <U+201C><U+D32C><U+B4E4> <U+C544><U+C26C><U+C6CC>~ (''Girls completed a formal House action "disappointed fans~'')] ''Newsen''. Retrieved May 24, 2010.</ref> During the group's promotions, members Jessica, Tiffany and Seohyun were featured on a mini-album released by Roommate, a one-man band from [[S.M. Entertainment|Purple Communication]]. The mini-album was titled ''Roommate: Emotional Band Aid'', and was released on December 1, 2008. The song performed by the three girls, titled "Oppa Nappa" ({{lang|ko|<U+C624><U+BE60> <U+B098><U+BE60>}}; literally, ''Bad Brother''), was digitally released before the album in April 2008. The song was performed live on SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'', KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'', and Mnet ''[[M! Countdown]]''.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200805221519191002&search=title&searchstring=<U+FFFD>%EA%B7%9A%EC%8A%A4<U+FFFD>%EB%93%A4%EB%A3%86<U+FFFD>%EB%93%95%EB%B3%B4%E5%A4%9C%EB%85%B7%EB%B1%9C<U+FFFD>%EB%97%A9%EB%BC%BC%E5%9A%A5%EB%85%B7%EB%87%A1<U+FFFD>%EB%9A%B3%ED%89%AA<U+FFFD>%E2%91%A2%EB%A6%B6<U+FFFD>%EC%84%87%ED%89%B8age=3 [<U+D3EC><U+D1A0><U+C5D4>&#93;3<U+4EBA>3<U+8272>, <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+C11C><U+D604>-<U+D2F0><U+D30C><U+B2C8>-<U+C81C><U+C2DC><U+CE74> (Girls' Generation Jessica Tiffany Seohyun]</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200805050845271001 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+C81C><U+D2F0><U+D604> <U+2018><U+C624><U+BE60><U+B098><U+BE60>' <U+C2E0><U+ACE0><U+C2DD> <U+C5EC><U+C778><U+C758> <U+D5A5><U+AE30> <U+BB3C><U+C52C> (Girls' Generation JeTiHyun "Oppa Nappa")]</ref> Later in the year, the three members released "Mabinogi" (It's Fantastic!) together as the theme song for the [[Nexon Co. Ltd.|Nexon]] game ''[[Mabinogi (video game)|Mabinogi]]'', with Tiffany participating in the music video.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://media.paran.com/enter/view.kth?dirnews=1906281&year=2008&dir=5&rtlog=MV <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+B9C8><U+BE44><U+B178><U+AE30> <U+C0C1><U+D07C> <U+C8FC><U+C81C><U+ACE1> <U+2018><U+ACF5><U+AC1C>' (Mabinogi Theme Song by Girls' Generation Released)]</ref> Mnet reality show ''[[Factory Girl (TV series)|Factory Girl]]'' chronicled the members working as interns at fashion magazine ''[[Elle Girl]]''.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://mnet.mnet.com/NProgram/factorygirl/?bidx=factorygirl Factory Girl <U+2013> official website]</ref> The program began airing in early October.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://mydaily.co.kr/news/read.html?newsid=200809301119101115 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C774><U+C81C><U+B294> <U+D328><U+C158> <U+C5D0><U+B514><U+D130><U+B85C> <U+BCC0><U+C2E0> (''Girls' Generation, Now Becoming Fashion Editors'')]. ''MyDaily''. September 30, 2008. Retrieved October 3, 2008.</ref> In late 2008, the group also participated in the [[SMTown Live '08]] concert along with other [[SM Town]] artists.

===2009: ''Gee'', ''Genie'', first Asian tour and rising popularity===
[[File:LG<U+C804><U+C790> <U+BAA8><U+BC14><U+C77C> <U+C6D4><U+B4DC><U+CEF5> - <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+CD95><U+D558><U+ACF5><U+C5F0>.jpg|thumb|Girls' Generation performing "Genie" at the LG Mobile Worldcup in 2009.]]
A teaser video was released in January 2009 and the first single "[[Gee (Girls' Generation song)|Gee]]" released soon after. "Gee" topped [[Cyworld]]'s hourly music chart on the release day.<ref>{{ko icon}} Lee, Soo-hyeon. [http://star.moneytoday.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2009010516291222142&type=1 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+C2E0><U+ACE1> '<U+C9C0>', <U+ACF5><U+AC1C> <U+B3D9><U+C2DC> <U+C2F8><U+C774><U+C6D4><U+B4DC> <U+C2E4><U+C2DC><U+AC04> 1<U+C704> (''Girls' Generation's New Song "Gee" Tops Cyworld's Hourly Chart After Release'')]. ''MoneyToday''. January 5, 2009. Retrieved January 5, 2009.</ref> The song also went number one on all major digital music charts within two days.<ref name="chart6">{{ko icon}} Park, Young-woong. [http://www.mydaily.co.kr/news/read.html?newsid=200901071156201131 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 'Gee' <U+ACF5><U+AC1C> 2<U+C77C> <U+B9CC><U+C5D0> <U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+CC28><U+D2B8> '<U+C62C><U+D0AC>' (''Girls' Generation's "Gee" Does Chart "All-Kill" 2 Days After Release'')]. ''MyDaily''. January 7, 2009. Retrieved January 7, 2009.</ref> The group began its album promotion in January 2009 on MBC ''[[Show! Music Core]]'' where they sang their new lead single "Gee" and the track "[[Way to Go! (Himnae)|Way to Go!]]", another song from their mini-album. A week after its release, "Gee" went #1 on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]''.<ref>Lee, Jeong-hyeok. [http://sports.chosun.com/news/news.htm?name=/news/entertainment/200901/20090117/91q22202.htm '<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>', KBS<U+C640> <U+AC08><U+B4F1>?...2<U+C8FC> <U+C5F0><U+C18D> <U+CD9C><U+C5F0> <U+C548><U+D574> (''Girls' Generation, KBS Conflict?...Two Weeks of No-Shows'')]. ''Sports Chosun''. January 16, 2009. Retrieved January 16, 2009.</ref>  "Gee" also went to #1 on SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'' a week after their return. "Gee" went on to become a phenomenal hit, breaking the record for consecutive number one wins on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' with nine consecutive wins, as well as receiving a triple crown on SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]''. The song then broke the record by staying on top a seventh week,<ref>Lee Soo-oon. [http://www.etnews.co.kr/news/detail.html?id=200902240086&mc=m_002_00002 (<U+BBA4><U+C9C1><U+D074><U+B7FD>)<U+CE74><U+B77C>, <U+B2E8><U+C228><U+C5D0> 2<U+C704> <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> 'Gee' <U+B204><U+B97C><U+AE4C> (''(Music Club) Kara, Second in Moments; Can They Overcome Girls' Generation's "Gee"'')]. ''ETNews''. February 25, 2009. Retrieved February 24, 2009.</ref> and remained in the position for an eighth week. It also tied<ref name=mbtie>Yang, Seung-joon. [http://spn.edaily.co.kr/entertain//newsRead.asp?sub_cd=EA21&newsid=01308726589594784&DirCode=0010201 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, '<U+BBA4><U+BC45>' 7<U+C8FC> <U+C5F0><U+C18D> 1<U+C704>...<U+C96C><U+C5BC><U+B9AC><U+C640> <U+CD5C><U+C7A5> <U+AE30><U+B85D> '<U+D0C0><U+C774>' (''Girls' Generation, 'Music Bank' 7-Week Continuous #1...'Ties' Jewelry's Record'')]. ''EDaily''. February 27, 2009. Retrieved March 3, 2009.</ref> then broke the record for longest-running #1 on ''Music Bank'', beating the 7-week record previously set by [[Jewelry (band)|Jewelry]] in 2008 with "One More Time".<ref name=mbtie />  "Gee" achieved its ninth #1 on the show on March 13, 2009. [[S.M. Entertainment]] stated that over 100,000 copies of the mini-album were shipped to stores, while sales analyst company Hanteo reported sales in excess of 30,000 copies within the first 10 days of its release. The track also showed strength on other charts, topping the ''Mujikon'', ''Melon'' and ''Mnet'' charts for eight consecutive weeks, the ''Dosirak'' chart for seven weeks, the ''Muse'' chart for six weeks, and the ''Baksu'' chart for four weeks.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://nabee.tistory.com/682 <U+B098><U+BE44><U+C758> <U+C5EC><U+D589> :: <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+2013> Gee (<U+D2B8><U+B808><U+C77C><U+B7EC>, <U+BBA4><U+C9C1><U+BE44><U+B514><U+C624>) / 1<U+C704> <U+AE30><U+B85D> <U+C815><U+B9AC>]</ref><ref name="news.jkn.co.kr">{{ko icon}} [http://news.jkn.co.kr/article/news/20090313/7310014.htm <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 9<U+C8FC> <U+C5F0><U+C18D> 1<U+C704> <U+CC28><U+C9C0> <U+2018><U+C74C><U+BC18><U+00B7><U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+BAA8><U+B450> <U+B450><U+AC01>' (Girls' Generation 9 Consecutive No.1 Wins.)]</ref>

After a short break, SM Entertainment announced that the group would be back with a new mini-album sporting a "[[Marine (military)|Marine]] Girl" concept. The new single was to be titled "[[Tell Me Your Wish (Genie) (song)|Tell Me Your Wish (Genie)]]", with the full mini-album being released digitally on June 22, 2009.<ref name="Genie release">{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200906231509181002 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+C81C><U+B85C><U+C13C> <U+B17C><U+B780><U+C5D0> <U+C74C><U+BC18> <U+BC1C><U+B9E4><U+C77C> 29<U+C77C><U+B85C> <U+C5F0><U+AE30> <U+2018><U+BB38><U+C81C> <U+BD80><U+BD84> <U+C0AD><U+C81C>'], Newsen.com. June 23, 2009. Retrieved May 20, 2010.</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} Jang, Hwi-jae. [http://www.todaykorea.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=73554 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+D0C0><U+C774><U+D2C0> <U+ACE1> <U+2018><U+C18C><U+C6D0><U+C744> <U+B9D0><U+D574><U+BD10>'<U+B85C> <U+D65C><U+B3D9> <U+C7AC><U+AC1C> (''Girls' Generation, Title Song "Tell Me Your Wish" for Comeback'')]. ''TodayKorea''. June 17, 2009. Retrieved June 17, 2009.</ref> The group started their promotional activities on June 26, 2009, appearing on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]''.<ref name=cnb>{{ko icon}} [http://www.cnbnews.com/category/read_org.html?bcode=82226 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 25<U+C77C> <U+B450> <U+BC88><U+C9F8> <U+C2F1><U+AE00> '<U+C18C><U+C6D0><U+C744> <U+B9D0><U+D574><U+BD10>' <U+ACF5><U+AC1C> (''Girls' Generation'', Second mini-album ''Tell Me Your Wish (Genie)'' Released on 22nd'')]. ''Korea Precious News.com''. October 16, 2009 . Retrieved October 16, 2009.</ref> The performance was followed by follow-up comeback performances on MBC ''[[Show! Music Core]]'' and SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]'' on June 27 and 28, 2009. The physical release of ''Genie'' was delayed by SM Entertainment in order to redo the album art, and was released four days later on June 29, 2009.<ref name="Genie release"/> Their first win for their single "Sowoneul Malhaebwa (Genie)" was obtained at the July 10, 2009 episode of KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]''. Their second award was claimed on the July 12, 2009 episode of SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]''. Within a few days, the song topped on 10 different digital music charts.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://sports.khan.co.kr/news/sk_index.html?cat=view&art_id=200907011938573&sec_id=540301&sk_id=08 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C804> <U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+CC28><U+D2B8> 1<U+C704> <U+C11D><U+AD8C>. <U+B610> <U+2018><U+C62C> <U+D0AC><U+2019><U+2026>. (''Girls' Generation' Tops All Digital Charts, "All Kill" Again...'')]. ''SportsKhan''. July 1, 2009. Retrieved July 16, 2009.</ref> The track proved to be a success as it conquered various music sites, including Melon, Dosirak, Mnet, and Bugs, and it was number one on the weekly charts and the SKT ringtone weekly charts of the first week of July.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200907101958341002&search=title&searchstring=%BC%D2%B3%E0%BD%C3%B4%EB <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+BBA4><U+BC45> 1<U+C704> <U+2018><U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+C74C><U+BC18> <U+BCA8> <U+BC29><U+C1A1><U+D69F><U+C218> <U+C774><U+C5B4> <U+AC00><U+C694><U+CC28><U+D2B8> <U+C62C><U+D0AC>' ('SNSD Music Bank No.1 "Online, offline, ringtone, broadcast numbers and music charts all-kill")]</ref> The mini-album sold an estimated 50,000+ copies in its first week after released (almost double the numbers from the first-week sales of ''Gee''), an unusual feat for any Korean girl group.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200907071134541002 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+AC00><U+C694><U+ACC4> <U+C62C><U+D0AC> <U+2018><U+C74C><U+BC18> <U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+BCA8> <U+BC29><U+C1A1><U+D69F><U+C218> <U+BAA8><U+B450> 1<U+C704> <U+C2F9><U+C4F8><U+C774>' ('SNSD Commits an Industry All-Kill: Music Sales, Online Sales, Ringtones, Broadcast')]</ref> The albums went to sell over 200,000 as of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+AC00><U+C694><U+ACC4> <U+C62C><U+D0AC> <U+2018><U+C74C><U+BC18> <U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+BCA8> <U+BC29><U+C1A1><U+D69F><U+C218> <U+BAA8><U+B450> 1<U+C704> <U+C2F9><U+C4F8><U+C774>|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200907071134541002}}</ref>

On November 2009, [[S.M. Entertainment]] announced the group's [[Into the New World (concert)|Into The New World Tour]]. The tickets for the tour went on sale on November 19,<ref name="announce1">{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent9&idxno=2009111110054389701|title=Girls' Generation to embark on Asia tour next month|last=Lynn|first=Kim|date=November 11, 2009|publisher=''Asia Economy''|accessdate=November 29, 2009}}</ref> and sold out in 3 minutes.<ref name="Sellout 3 min">{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/11/25/2009112500702.html|title=Girls' Generation Gig Sells Out in 3 Minutes|date=November 24, 2009|publisher=''Chosun Ilbo''|accessdate=November 29, 2009}}</ref> The tour initially consisted of two Korean shows on December 19 and 20, 2009.<ref name="Announce">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/11/178_55332.html|title=Girls<U+2019> Generation to Hold Asian Tour|last=Han Sang|first=Hee|date=November 11, 2009|publisher=''[[Korea Times]]''|accessdate=November 29, 2009}}</ref> The tour began at Seoul's Olympic Park Fencing Stadium on December 19 and 20 and continued onto other Asian cities including Shanghai.<ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent9&idxno=2009111110054389701 Girls' Generation to embark on Asia tour next month <U+2013> <U+C544><U+C2DC><U+C544><U+ACBD><U+C81C><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===2010: ''Oh! / Run Devil Run'', Japanese debut and ''Hoot''===
Later in January, SM Entertainment confirmed the release of ''[[Oh! (Girls' Generation album)|Oh!]]'', the group's second full-length album, to be on January 28.<ref name="OH/ANNOUNCE">{{ko icon}}{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.co.kr/NEWKHSITE/data/html_dir/2010/01/22/201001220013.asp|title=Girls Generation to release 2nd album|date=January 21, 2010|work=Korea Herald|accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref> The lead single "[[Oh! (Girls' Generation song)|Oh!]]" was digitally released on January 25 with the music video being released two days later.<ref>{{ko icon}}[http://thestar.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/01/27/2010012700482.html <U+CE58><U+C5B4><U+B9AC><U+B354><U+B85C> <U+BCC0><U+C2E0><U+D55C> <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+2018>Oh!' <U+BBA4><U+C9C1><U+BE44><U+B514><U+C624> 27<U+C77C> <U+ACF5><U+AC1C>! (''Girls' Generation's "Oh!" M/V Released on January 27!'')]. Released, No.1 on Chart within 10 Minutes. ''JK News''. January 25, 2010. Retrieved January 24, 2010.</ref> On January 30, the group started promotions with the recording of MBC ''[[Show! Music Core]]''.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://sstv.freechal.com/News/Detail.aspx?cSn=1&pSn=76021 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> '<U+C1FC>! <U+C74C><U+C545><U+C911><U+C2EC>'<U+C73C><U+B85C> <U+CCAB> <U+CEF4><U+BC31> <U+BB34><U+B300> (''Girls' Generation's 1st "Oh!" performance on "Show! Music Core")].''SSTV''. February 3, 2010. Retrieved January 30, 2010.</ref> The broadcast of the performance experienced a blackout near the end, to which MBC made the whole performance available online in response.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://sstv.freechal.com/News/Detail.aspx?cSn=1&pSn=76061 '<U+C74C><U+C545><U+C911><U+C2EC>' <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> 'Oh!' <U+D074><U+B9B0><U+BC84><U+C804> <U+BB34><U+B8CC><U+C11C><U+BE44><U+C2A4> <U+C2E4><U+C2DC> ("Show! Music Core" starts to provide Girls' Generation's 1st "Oh!" complete performance'')].''SSTV''. February 3, 2010. Retrieved January 30, 2010.</ref>

With "Oh!", the group went on to win five consecutive K-charts on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'', as well as achieving a triple crown on SBS ''[[The Music Trend|Inkigayo]]''.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.tvdaily.co.kr/read.php3?aid=127746059568685002 '<U+BBA4><U+C9C1><U+BC45><U+D06C>' <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, '<U+C0C1><U+BC18><U+AE30> <U+ACB0><U+C0B0> K<U+CC28><U+D2B8> 1<U+C704> <U+2013> <U+D2F0><U+BE0C><U+C774><U+B370><U+C77C><U+B9AC> ("Music Bank" Girls' Generation, '1st place on Looking Back on the First Half (of the year) K Chart'..'Dominated the Music Industry'')]</ref> "Oh!" also went on to win the ''Music Bank'' half-year K-chart, coming in at second on Hanteo's first half album sales chart,<ref name="star.mt.co.kr">{{ko icon}} [http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2010063011010111636&type=1&outlink=1 <U+C18C><U+C2DC> '<U+C624>!', <U+C0C1><U+BC18><U+AE30> <U+C74C><U+C6D0><U+D310><U+B9E4><U+B3C4> 1<U+C704> '<U+D2B8><U+B9AC><U+D50C><U+D06C><U+B77C><U+C6B4>' (''Soshi 'Oh!', 'Triple Crown' 1st place in First Half Music Sales.'')]</ref> and also winning the end-of-year K-chart.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} The music video ranked as the number-one most-viewed [[YouTube]] video in Korea by the end of 2010. It was also number one in [[Hong Kong]] and made the top ten in both the [[Taiwan]] and [[Japan]] rankings.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://news.nate.com/view/20101216n12455 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> '<U+C624>' <U+BBA4><U+BE44>, <U+C720><U+D29C><U+BE0C> <U+B9CE><U+C774> <U+BCF8> <U+B3D9><U+C601><U+C0C1> 1<U+C704> <U+CC28><U+C9C0>] ''Nate''. December 16, 2010. Retrieved December 16, 2010.</ref>

[[File:SNSD 2.jpg|thumb|left|Girls' Generation at an LG event in 2010.]]
Starting on March 11, 2010, photos of the members were released online showcasing a dark concept, dubbed "Black SoShi".<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://osen.mt.co.kr/news/view.html?gid=G1003120027 <U+BE14><U+B799><U+C18C><U+C2DC> <U+D0DC><U+C5F0>-<U+C11C><U+D604>, <U+B3C4><U+B3C4>-<U+C2DC><U+D06C> <U+B9E4><U+B825> <U+BB3C><U+C52C> (''Black SNSD Taeyeon-Seohyun "Glamorous and Elegant" look'')]. ''Osen''. March 12, 2010. Retrieved March 11, 2010.</ref> A teaser video was released on March 16, with the new single [[Run Devil Run (Girls' Generation song)|Run Devil Run]] being released as a [[music download|digital single]] on March 17. Mid-June, it was announced that the group had signed contracts in May, and would begin working under Universal Music Japan's record label Nayutawave Records for their Japanese promotions, with their first Japanese single expected to be released in September 2010.<ref name="sanspo.com_Japan">{{ja icon}} [http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/100611/gnj1006110506018-n1.htm <U+201C><U+97D3><U+201D><U+52D5><U+7F8E><U+811A><U+FF19><U+4EBA><U+5A18><U+3001><U+FF18><U+6708><U+306B><U+65E5><U+672C><U+30C7><U+30D3><U+30E5><U+30FC> (1/2<U+30DA><U+30FC><U+30B8>) (''Korea's 9 "beautiful-legged" ladies, August Japan Debut'')], sanspo.com. June 11, 2010. Retrieved June 11, 2010.</ref><ref name="Japan_debut">{{ja icon}} [http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/entertainment/77100/full/?cat_id=tw "Beautiful-legged" Girls' Generation make their Japanese Advancement'']. oricon.co.jp. June 11, 2010.</ref><ref>Han Sang-hee: 'heir Japan debut'</ref> Girls' Generation began promotion in Japan in August. "<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+5230><U+6765><U+FF5E><U+521D><U+6765><U+65E5><U+8A18><U+5FF5><U+76E4><U+FF5E>" (''Girls' Generation's Arrival <U+FF5E> First Time in Japan Commemoration Disc <U+FF5E>''), a DVD featuring seven of the group's music videos as well as special bonus footage, was released on August 11, with the special edition of the DVD containing a pink glowstick as well as a pass to the Girls' Generation debut at the [[Ariake Coliseum|Tokyo Ariake Colliseum]] on August 25.<ref name="news.nate.com">{{ko icon}} [http://news.nate.com/view/20100611n03353 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 8<U+C6D4> <U+CD08><U+B300><U+D615> <U+C1FC><U+CF00><U+C774><U+C2A4><U+B85C> <U+65E5> <U+C9C4><U+CD9C> <U+C120><U+C5B8> (''Girls' Generation, Announcing their Advancement with a Mega Showcase in August'')]. Nate. June 11, 2010.</ref> In the first week after release, the DVD sold 23,000 copies, ranking fourth on the weekly DVD Oricon ranking and third on the weekly music DVD ranking,<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20100817-00000001-wow-ent <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+65E5>DVD<U+304C><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3>4<U+4F4D> <U+201C><U+65B0><U+4EBA><U+201D><U+3067><U+306F><U+7570><U+4F8B><U+306E>4<U+4E07><U+679A><U+51FA><U+8377> (Girls' Generation ranks 4th on ORICON & ships out 40,000 copies as rookies)]</ref> and made Girls' Generation the first female K-pop group to make the Oricon DVD Top-5 ranking.<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/rankmusic/79147/full/ <U+201C><U+7F8E><U+811A><U+201D><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+30FC><U+30D7><U+30FB><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001><U+97D3><U+56FD><U+5973><U+6027><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+2015><U+30D7><U+521D><U+306E>DVD<U+7DCF><U+5408>TOP5<U+5165><U+308A>(SNSD is First Korean Female Group to place in the Top 5 for ORICON's total DVD ranking)]</ref> Amidst their Japanese activities, the group also participated in the ''[[SMTown Live '10 World Tour]]'' alongside their label-mates on August 21 at [[Olympic Stadium (Seoul)|Seoul Jamsil Olympic Stadium]].<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2010/07/178_68702.html ''SM Entertainment to launch world tour''] ''[[The Korea Times]]''. July 2, 2010. Retrieved July 5, 2010.</ref> They participated in the subsequent Shanghai, Los Angeles, Paris and Tokyo stops as well.<ref>Jonathan Hicap: ''[http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/265001/sm-entertainment-artists-including-super-junior-hold-world-tour SM Entertainment artists including Super Junior to hold world tour]''. ''Manila Bulletin''. July 3, 2010. Retrieved July 4, 2010</ref>

On August 25, the group held their first showcase in Tokyo Ariake Colliseum.<ref>{{ja icon}}[http://www.daily.co.jp/newsflash/2010/08/25/0003358802.shtml <U+97D3><U+56FD><U+306E><U+4EBA><U+6C17><U+FF19><U+4EBA><U+7D44><U+30FB><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+304C><U+65E5><U+672C><U+4E0A><U+9678> (Finally the veil is lifted! 22,000 people cheer for Shoujo Jidai!)]</ref> With an initial 10,000 fans invited, it was reported to be the most large-scale plan for a Korean artist debuting in Japan.<ref name="news.nate.com"/> However, due to high number of expected attendees, the group's management announced that the showcase would take place three times in the same day rather than once to accommodate the large amount of fans.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://media.daum.net/entertain/music/view.html?cateid=1033&newsid=20100819081514136&p=newsen <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+65E5> <U+C1FC><U+CF00><U+C774><U+C2A4> 1<U+D68C> 1<U+B9CC><U+BA85><U+2192>3<U+D68C> 2<U+B9CC><U+BA85> <U+ACF5><U+C5F0> <U+CD94><U+AC00> <U+2018><U+AD00><U+C2EC><U+D3ED><U+BC1C>' (Girls' Generation's Showcase Increases from 1 Show to 3 Shows)]</ref> The group sang five of their Korean tracks at each of the showcases, and the total number of attendees over all three shows were estimated to be at least 22,000.<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/flash/KFullFlash20100825052.html <U+7F8E><U+811A><U+304C><U+30A6><U+30EA><U+3067><U+3059><U+3000><U+300C><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+300D><U+3064><U+3044><U+306B><U+65E5><U+672C><U+3067><U+201C><U+89E3><U+7981><U+201D> (Matching Beautiful Legs "Girls' Generation" Opens in Japan)]</ref> At this showcase, the "Genie" Japanese music video was also revealed publicly for the first time, with the teaser having been released a few days prior on August 20.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201008201223531002 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+65E5><U+B370><U+BDD4> <U+C2F1><U+AE00> <U+2018><U+C9C0><U+B2C8>' <U+D2F0><U+C800> <U+ACF5><U+AC1C>, <U+D55C><U+AD6D><U+C11C><U+B3C4> <U+AD00><U+C2EC><U+D3ED><U+BC1C> (Sonyeo Sidae Releases their Japanese Single 'GENIE' Teaser Video, Also Attracts Attention from the South Koreans)] ''Newsen''. Retrieved September 4, 2010</ref> Their Japanese debut single "Genie" debuted at the fifth spot on the same day of its release on the Daily [[Oricon]] Charts and later rose to the second position on the Daily Charts some time later, earning the group a fourth position on the Oricon weekly ranking.<ref name="chosunonline.com">{{ja icon}} [http://www.chosunonline.com/entame/20100916000034 <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001><U+65E5><U+672C><U+306E><U+97F3><U+697D><U+30C1><U+30E3><U+30FC><U+30C8><U+3092><U+5E2D><U+5DFB> (Shoujo Jidai, Conquering Japan's Music Charts)]</ref><ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20100909000851 ''Girls' Generation debuts successfully in Japan''] ''The Korea Herald'', 9. September 2010.</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.tvdaily.co.kr/read.php3?aid=128425210287178002 <U+C18C><U+C2DC> <U+D2F0><U+D30C><U+B2C8>, <U+C77C><U+BCF8><U+C5D0><U+C11C><U+B3C4> '<U+C0B4><U+C778> <U+B208><U+C6C3><U+C74C>'<U+C73C><U+B85C> <U+7537><U+5FC3> <U+B179><U+C5EC> (Soshi Tiffany, 'Eye Smile' Melted Male Hearts Even in Japan)]</ref> The group also hit the number-one spots on Japan iTunes' music video chart and both the ''Rekochoku'' daily video clip chart and incoming movie daily ranking chart a day later.<ref name="barks.jp">{{ja icon}} [http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000064062 <U+201C><U+7F8E><U+811A><U+FF06><U+7F8E><U+30D2><U+30C3><U+30D7><U+201D><U+97D3><U+56FD><U+306E><U+30AC><U+30FC><U+30EB><U+30BA><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+30FC><U+30D7><U+304C><U+30EC><U+30B3><U+30C1><U+30E7><U+30AF><U+52D5><U+753B><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+5E2D><U+5DFB> (Korean Girl Groups Dominate Rekochoku Video Rankings)]</ref> With pre-orders amounting to 80,000, the single sold an estimated 45,000 copies in the first week after release.<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/rankmusic/80014/full/ K-POP<U+30AC><U+30FC><U+30EB><U+30BA><U+672C><U+547D><U+30FB><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001><U+65E5><U+672C><U+30C7><U+30D3><U+30E5><U+30FC><U+4F5C><U+304C><U+6B74><U+4EE3><U+6700><U+9AD8><U+8A18><U+9332> (Shoujo Jidai Breaks 2 Records on Oricon and Sells 45000 Copies of GENIE)]</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.hankyung.com/news/app/newsview.php?aid=2010090936807 `<U+C544><U+C2DC><U+C544> NO1 <U+AC78><U+ADF8><U+B8F9>` <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+65E5> <U+B370><U+BDD4> <U+C2F1><U+AE00> `GENIE` 1<U+C704>! (Asia's No.1 Girl Group Sonyeo Sidae Takes 1st Place With Debut Single!)]</ref> On October 20, 2010, the group released their second Japanese single, "[[Gee (Girls' Generation song)|Gee]]".<ref>{{jp icon}}[http://www.smtown.jp/news/50/88 (''Shoujo Jidai's (SNSD) <U+2018>Gee' album cover revealed (UPDATE: MV Teaser!'')] ''SM Town Japan''. September 30, 2010. Retrieved October 1, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://satsuki.musicdb.gr.jp/all_info/ranking_weekly/WeeklyRankingAction.do?term=2010s&weeklyCd=20101026&rankKbn=50|title=RIAJ Digital Track Chart: Chart issue October&nbsp;26, 2010|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|accessdate=October 29, 2010|language=Japanese}}</ref> A week after the release of their Japanese single, the group released their third Korean mini-album, ''[[Hoot (EP)|Hoot]]'' on October 27, 2010, consisting of five tracks.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.mydaily.co.kr/news/read.html?newsid=201010190722181137 "<U+C18C><U+C2DC> 3<U+C9D1> <U+BBF8><U+B2C8> <U+C568><U+BC94> <U+D6D7> <U+D2F0><U+C800> <U+C774><U+BBF8><U+C9C0> <U+00B7> <U+C74C><U+C6D0> <U+C804><U+ACA9> <U+ACF5><U+AC1C>... <U+B4DC><U+B514><U+C5B4> <U+CEF4><U+BC31>"] ''My Daily''. Retrieved October 21, 2010.</ref> The video for lead single, "[[Hoot (song)|Hoot]]", a song originally written in English as "Bulletproof", was released on October 28.<ref name="hitquarters.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_LHJQ_A.html |title=Q&A on K-pop with Lars Halvor Jensen |publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id = F4-SxcCO5d0|title = "Hoot" Music Video}}</ref> Girls' Generation commenced their promotional activities with a comeback stage on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' on October 29.<ref name="mtvk">{{cite web|author=Sunny Kim |url=http://www.mtvk.com/2010/10/27/super-juniors-siwon-to-make-a-special-appearance-in-girls-generations-hoot-mv |title=Super Junior<U+2019>s Siwon To Make A Special Appearance In Girls Generation<U+2019>s "Hoot" MV! &#124; MTV K <U+2013> K-Pop, Korean entertainment, music videos, interviews, music |publisher=MTV K |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2011}}</ref> "Hoot" quickly rose to the top of the charts and received the number-one spot numerous times on music shows, proving to be another successful release for the group.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/ Gaon Chart] ''[[Gaon Chart]]''. Retrieved November 5, 2010.</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010112117083622413 "<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, "(<U+D2F0>)<U+D30C><U+B2C8><U+C57C> <U+B610> 1<U+C704> <U+D588><U+C5B4>" 3<U+C8FC> <U+C5F0><U+C18D> <U+ACF5><U+C911><U+D30C> <U+C11D><U+AD8C>" (Sonyeo Sidae, "(Ti)Fany! We got no.1 again!" Conquered First Place Three Consecutive Weeks)]</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://joynews.inews24.com/php/news_view.php?g_serial=536165&g_menu=700091 <U+C62C><U+D574><U+C758> <U+BC85><U+C2A4><U+BBA4><U+C9C1> <U+C5B4><U+C6CC><U+B4DC> '<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>']</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.hankyung.com/news/app/newsview.php?aid=201011089612l&sid=0107&nid=007&ltype=1 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> `<U+D6D7>`, <U+AC01><U+C885> <U+C74C><U+C6D0><U+CC28><U+D2B8>-<U+C9C0><U+C0C1><U+D30C> <U+BC29><U+C1A1> <U+C62C><U+D0AC> (Girls Generation "Hoot" Chart All-Kill)]</ref> The group simultaneously promoted "Hoot" and "Gee" in Korea and Japan respectively, and participated in Japanese music broadcasts such as the [[FNS Music Festival]], where they performed their two Japanese singles, "[[Gee (Girls' Generation song)|Gee]]" and "Genie" on December 4. On December 22, 2010, "[[Hoot (EP)|Hoot]]" was repackaged with additional tracks from previous albums and released in Japan. The release rose to the second position on the Oricon charts and sold 21,000 copies on the first day, faring surprisingly well considering that all the included tracks were entirely in Korean.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent99&idxno=2010122219030738196 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, '<U+D6D7>' <U+BC1C><U+B9E4> <U+B2F9><U+C77C> 2<U+B9CC><U+C7A5><U+00B7><U+00B7><U+65E5><U+C624><U+B9AC><U+CF58> 2<U+C704> '<U+C774><U+B840><U+C801>' (Sonyeo Sidae "Hoot" Ranks Second On Oricon Daily Chart)]</ref> On December 9, 2010, the group attended the [[Golden Disk Awards]] and was awarded three awards including the Disk Daesang (Album of the Year) for their 2nd album ''[[Oh! (Girls' Generation album)|Oh!]]''. The group also became the first girl group to have both a Disk Daesang (2010) and Digital Daesang (2009). On December 15, 2010, the group attended the [[MelOn Music Awards]] winning the ''Best Dressed Singer'' award and ''Hot Trend Song'' award for, "Hoot", as well as the ''Artist of the Year'' award. This would be the second consecutive 'Artist of the Year' award for the group. They topped the ''Hanteo'' annual ''Singer Award'' chart for 2010.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://hanteo.com/rank/nHanteo_award_s2.asp?part=singer] ''Hanteo''. Retrieved December 27, 2010.</ref> The group was named on Asia Today's list of ''50 Korean power leaders for 2011'' at the number forty-fourth spot, being the only idol group from the list.<ref name="<U+C544><U+C2DC><U+C544><U+D22C><U+B370><U+C774> <U+C120><U+C815>...<U+D55C><U+AD6D><U+C758> <U+D30C><U+C6CC><U+B9AC><U+B354> 50<U+C778>"/> Girls' Generation was designated "Artist of the Year" by Dosirak, Soribada, Korea Gallup, Hanteo and Sport Korea and also won ''Best Song of The Year'' with "Oh!" at Monkey 3.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://news.nate.com/view/20101220n07523 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 2010<U+B144> <U+CD5C><U+ACE0><U+C758> <U+C544><U+D2F0><U+C2A4><U+D2B8> <U+B4F1><U+ADF9>] ''Nate''. Retrieved December 20, 2010.</ref><ref>{{ko icon}} [http://news.nate.com/view/20101221n09118 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 2<U+B144> <U+C5F0><U+C18D> <U+AD6D><U+BBFC><U+C774> <U+BF51><U+C740> '<U+C62C><U+D574><U+C758> <U+AC00><U+C218>'<U+B85C> <U+C120><U+C815>] ''Nate''. December 21, 2010. Retrieved December 21, 2010.</ref>

===2011: ''Girls' Generation'', touring, international expansion and ''The Boys''===
[[File:SNSD Visual Dream World Premiere Showcase (2).jpg|thumb|Girls' Generation at Visual Dream World Premiere Showcase.]]
In latter half of January, it was announced that the group would be returning to the Japanese market through the release of their Japanese version of "[[Run Devil Run (Girls' Generation song)|Run Devil Run]]" as a digital single, released on January 25, 2011.<ref>{{ko icon}} [http://news.nate.com/view/20110118n04083 <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, '<U+B7F0> <U+B370><U+BE4C> <U+B7F0>' <U+BE14><U+B799><U+C18C><U+C2DC><U+B85C> <U+65E5> <U+B610> <U+AC15><U+D0C0>] ''Nate''. January 18, 2011. Retrieved January 18, 2011.</ref> On January 20, 2011, at the 20th [[Seoul Music Awards]], the group received "Artist of the Year", the "Bonsang" prize", a "Popularity" award, and a "[[Korean Wave]] award". In doing this, Girls' Generation became one of four artists in Korean music history (the others being [[Seo Taiji]], [[Jo Sungmo]] and [[H.O.T.]]) to be named 'Artist of the Year' for two consecutive years. The group also became the only girl group in history to receive 'Artist of the Year' awards for the Seoul Music Awards, and [[MelOn Music Awards]] for two consecutive years. They also received two Daesang Awards at the Golden Disk Ceremony, one Digital Daesang (2009), and one Physical Album Sales Daesang (2010).<ref name="<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C11C><U+C6B8><U+AC00><U+C694><U+B300><U+C0C1> '<U+B300><U+C0C1>'... 4<U+AD00><U+C655> '<U+C601><U+C608>'">{{ko icon}} [http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2011012020554329072&type= <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C11C><U+C6B8><U+AC00><U+C694><U+B300><U+C0C1> '<U+B300><U+C0C1>'... 4<U+AD00><U+C655> '<U+C601><U+C608>'] ''Star News''. January 20, 2011. Retrieved January 21, 2011.</ref> On March 8, SM Japan updated their official website with information about the release of Girls' Generation third Japanese single and their first Japanese tour. It was stated that on April 27, Girls' Generation would be releasing their third Japanese single, "[[Mr. Taxi / Run Devil Run]]", which would include their first, original, Japanese song "[[Mr. Taxi / Run Devil Run|Mr. Taxi]]".<ref>[http://yeinjee.com/2011/girls-generation-mr-taxi-music-video/ Mr Taxi music video] ''YeinJee Asian Journal''. April 26, 2011.</ref> and the Japanese remake of their song "[[Run Devil Run (Girls' Generation song)|Run Devil Run]]". At the [[MTV Video Music Awards Japan|2011 MTV Video Music Aid Japan (VMAJ)]], Girls' Generation was nominated for three awards under the "Best Group Video", "Best Video Of The Year", and "Best Karaokee! Song" categories.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 VMAJ Nominee List|url=http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj/nominee/|publisher=Official MTV VIDEO MUSIC AID JAPAN Website|accessdate=July 13, 2011}}</ref> On July 2, it was announced that they had come out top in two out of the three nominated categories, winning "Best Group Video" and "Best Karaokee! Song" for the Japanese version of "Genie".<ref>{{cite web|title=ANNOUNCING THE WINNERS OF THIS YEAR'S MTV VMAJs|url=http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj/en/2011-07-04/4808|publisher=Official MTV VIDEO MUSIC AID JAPAN Website|accessdate=July 13, 2011}}</ref> On June 1, 2011, the group released its debut Japanese studio album, ''[[Girls' Generation (2011 album)|Girls' Generation]]''.<ref>[http://www.girls-generation.jp/mrtaxi/ad/album_ad.html] Retrieved May 16, 2011.</ref> The album was promoted via the groups first Japan tour entitled, [[The First Japan Arena Tour (Girls' Generation)|The 1st Japan Arena Tour]], which started in [[Osaka]] on May 31, 2011. A total of fourteen concerts in six cities would be held over a period of a month and a half.

''Girls' Generation'' was certified Platinum (250,000) by Recording Industry Association of Japan on June 14, 2011, making it the fifth Korean artist's album to do so after S.E.S, BoA, [[TVXQ]] and [[Kara (band)|KARA]]. ''Girls' Generation'' then was certified Double Platinum (500,000) on July 8, 2011, a first for any Korean girl group.<ref>{{jp icon}}{{cite web|title=RIAJ June 2011Award List|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/gold/201106.html|publisher=Recording Industry Association of Japan (RIAJ)|accessdate=July 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Girls' Generation 1st Japan album goes double platinum|url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?sec=ent0&a_id=2011070816463290163|accessdate=July 13, 2011|newspaper=10Asia|author=Lucia Hong|author2=Jessica Kim|agency=10Asia}}</ref>
The group also set a record for recording the highest sales of the FIRST album as a foreign artist in Japan. Girls' Generation is the fourth artist to obtained number-one spot on weekly album chart after BoA, TVXQ, and [[Big Bang]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s 1st Japanese Full Album to be Sold Over 500,000 Copies!|url=http://www.facebook.com/notes/smtown/girls-generations-1st-japanese-full-album-to-be-sold-over-500000-copies/218202211555954|publisher=Official SMTOWN Facebook|accessdate=July 13, 2011|language=Korean}}</ref> and became the third Korean act to surpass the 500,000 mark after BoA and TVXQ. As a result of their rising popularity, Girls' Generation became the highest earning foreign artist in Japan for the first half of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+3010><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+4E0A><U+534A><U+671F><U+3011><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001><U+6D77><U+5916><U+6B4C><U+624B>1<U+4F4D><U+306E>26<U+5104><U+5186><U+3000>K-POP<U+52E2><U+304C><U+5927><U+8E8D><U+9032>|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/rankmusic/89091/full/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=June 23, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> By the end of 2011, the album had sold over 728,000 copies.<ref>{{ja icon}} {{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2012-01-09/|title=2011<U+5E74>12<U+6708>26<U+65E5><U+FF5E>2012<U+5E74>01<U+6708>01<U+65E5><U+306E>CD<U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+9031><U+9593><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0>|language=Japanese | publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=January 7, 2011|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.generasia.com/wiki/Girls%27_Generation_(album)|title=Girls' Generation (album)|publisher=Generasia|accessdate=January 7, 2011|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref> The album was re-packaged, as "The Boys" on December 28, 2011. Their most successful album to date, it was certified 'Million' by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan|RIAJ]], and made the group the second Korean artist to earn this achievement in Japan since labelmate [[BoA]]'s ''"Best of Soul"'' in 2005, as well as being the first female group to do so.<ref name="asahi.com"/> The self-titled album was the fifth best selling album in Japan in 2011 <ref>[http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/12/oricon-announces-full-list-for-2011-yearly-album-ranking/ Oricon announces full list for <U+201C>2011 Yearly Album Ranking<U+201D><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and won ''Album of the Year'' at the [[2012 MTV Video Music Awards Japan]]. The lead single, "[[Mr. Taxi / Run Devil Run|Mr.&nbsp;Taxi]]", sold over 100,000 copies in its first week, beating out its predecessors, "Gee" and "Genie".<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+30C1><U+30E3><U+30F3><U+30FB><U+30B0><U+30F3><U+30BD><U+30AF><U+3001><U+6D77><U+5916><U+6B4C><U+624B><U+53F2><U+4E0A><U+521D><U+306E><U+30C7><U+30D3><U+30E5><U+30FC><U+4F5C><U+521D><U+767B><U+5834><U+9996><U+4F4D>|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/87299/full/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=June 16, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> The single also managed to clinch the number&nbsp;1 spot on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Japan Hot 100]] chart for two consecutive weeks and was nominated for Video of the Year at the [[2012 MTV Video Music Awards Japan]].<ref name="<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3> <U+8A71><U+984C><U+306E><U+65B0><U+66F2><U+304C><U+9996><U+4F4D><U+7372><U+5F97><U+FF01>">{{cite web|title=<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3> <U+8A71><U+984C><U+306E><U+65B0><U+66F2><U+304C><U+9996><U+4F4D><U+7372><U+5F97><U+FF01>|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/system/jp_charts/hot100/page:7|publisher=Billboard Japan|accessdate=June 16, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+306E><U+300C>MR.TAXI<U+300D><U+304C><U+3001>2<U+9031><U+9023><U+7D9A>1<U+4F4D><U+3092><U+8A18><U+9332><U+FF01>|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/system/jp_charts/hot100/page:6|publisher=Billboard Japan|accessdate=June 16, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref>

[[2011 Girls' Generation Asia Tour|Girls Generation 2nd Asian Tour]] was announced by S.M. Entertainment in June 2011. The tickets for the tour went on sale on June 7, 2011 on GMarket. On July 24,<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/07/143_91680.html Girls<U+2019> Generation <U+2015> it<U+2019>s the girls<U+2019> time!<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Girls' Generation was selected by SISA Press as "The Most Influential Entertainers in Korea" for the year 2011, after having placed sixth in 2010.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} Setting their sights on the international market, Girls' Generation signed a contract with [[Universal Music Group]] in 2011 to release [[United States]] material under [[Interscope Records]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?girls_generation_brings_the_boys_out_17554.aspx | title = Girls' Generation brings "The Boys" out | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = October 18, 2011}}</ref> ''The Boys'' was originally scheduled to be released through [[iTunes]] and various music websites in Asia, including its native country, Korea on October 5, 2011. But on September 30, it was revealed that the album's release has been postponed so as to bring about a worldwide album release.<ref>{{ko icon}}{{Cite news|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2011093019024680455&type=1&outlink=1|title=<U+C18C><U+C2DC>, 3<U+C9D1> <U+97D3><U+BC1C><U+B9E4><U+C5F0><U+AE30> <U+ACF5><U+C2DD><U+BC1C><U+D45C> "<U+7F8E><U+C568><U+BC94><U+BC1C><U+B9E4><U+B54C><U+BB38>"|date=January 21, 2010|newspaper=Star News|accessdate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> On October 10, it was confirmed that the album will be released on October 19, 2011 and comeback on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' on October 21, 2011.

[[File:Girls' Generation<U+2014>2011 SMtown concert.jpg|thumb|left|Girls' Generation performing "The Boys" at [[Madison Square Garden]], in October 2011.]]
The title track, "[[The Boys (Girls' Generation song)|The Boys]]", co-written by member Tiffany and produced by [[Teddy Riley]], famous for his work with [[Michael Jackson]], was released in both Korean and English, and eventually Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/notes/smtown/the-third-album-title-song-the-boys-will-be-released-worldwide-at-the-same-time-/253778391331669 |title=The Third Album Title Song, <U+2018>The Boys,<U+2019> will be Released Worldwide at the Same Time on October 4th! |publisher=Facebook.com |date=September 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 9, 2011}}</ref> Within minutes after the release of "The Boys", Girls' Generation achieved an "all-kill" status on all major on- and off-line music charts in Korea. Despite not charting on [[Billboard Hot 100]], the song managed to peak inside the Top 30 on the iTunes chart in the United States, selling over 21,000 copies and becoming one of the best selling K-Pop songs, at that time, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/viral-videos/508237/girls-generation-makes-big-us-debut-on-letterman-watch|title=Girls' Generation Makes Big U.S. Debut on 'Letterman': Watch|date=February 1, 2012|accessdate=July 8, 2012|publisher=billboard.com}}</ref> The same titled album sold 227,994 albums within twelve days in South Korea, becoming the best selling album in October and third best selling album in 2011. By the end of December, "The Boys" had sold a further 150,000 copies, bring its total to 385,348 copies, becoming the best selling album in South Korea in 2011.<ref name="The Boys">{{cite web |url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon/ |title=Girls' Generation's "The Boys" album sales figure |date=January 7, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6EjIuxMIx |archivedate=February 26, 2013 |accessdate=February 26, 2013}}</ref> The group began promotions on KBS ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' with "The Boys" and "[[Mr. Taxi / Run Devil Run|Mr. Taxi]]". On October 23, 2011, it was confirmed by the members at the New York City date of SMTown World Tour II, that "The Boys" maxi-Single would be released internationally on November 19, 2011, although the date was later moved to December 8, 2011.

With only two months of sales, "The Boys" managed to become the 10th best selling digital track in its native country of 2011, having sold 3,032,658 copies since its October release. As of April 2012, the album had sold over 410,000 copies in South Korea, setting a Gaon Chart record for the best selling, non-repackaged album in the chart's history.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}

It was announced on November 11, 2011, that the group would be releasing their first official Japanese photobook titled "Holiday". "Holiday", reached the number-one spot on the book sales ranking chart under the photograph collection category and sold 17,000 copies the first week after going on sale on November 30. It ranked eighteenth on the overall book sales ranks.  "The 1st Japan Arena Tour" was also made available on Blu-ray and DVD on December 14, 2011.

On December 7, 2011, it was announced that Girls' Generation will be releasing a re-packaged version of their debut Japanese album "Girls' Generation", which included a Japanese version of the "The Boys", and remixed versions of "The Great Escape", "Bad Girl", and "Mr.&nbsp;Taxi". It also contained the new song, "Time Machine". The album was released on December 28, 2011, and, collectively with the initial album, "Girls' Generation" passed sales of over 800,000, with shipments of 1&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+300C><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+300D><U+3001><U+65E5><U+672C><U+306E><U+521D><U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+304C><U+30DF><U+30EA><U+30AA><U+30F3><U+30BB><U+30E9><U+30FC><U+79D2><U+8AAD><U+307F>|url=http://www.asahi.com/showbiz/korea/AUT201112070050.html|language=Japanese}}</ref>

The album placed fifth on the Oricon Weekly CD Albums chart for the second week of January 2012 (Jan 9<U+2013>15)<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly rankings CD album January 15, 2012 Jan 09, 2012|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2012-01-23/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=January 26, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> and Oricon announced that it was the first time in history that an album by a Korean artist has placed in the Top 10 for seventeen weeks.  The previous record holder was the original soundtrack for the Korean drama <U+201C>Winter Sonata<U+201D>, which remained in the Top 10 for sixteen weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oricon Music News|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/music/2005790/full/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=January 26, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> Due to their Japanese releases, the group ranked fifth among Japanese artists in terms of monetary profit, the group had generated over 4.5 billion Yen (US$57 million) for 2011.<ref name="http">{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20120102n25988|title=[CDU ESL <U+C5F0><U+C608><U+B274><U+C2A4> <U+C789><U+AE00><U+B9AC><U+C2DC> <U+C2A4><U+CE94><U+B4E4>] <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300><U+00B7><U+CE74><U+B77C>, <U+C77C><U+BCF8> <U+D65C><U+B3D9> <U+C218><U+C775> <U+ACF5><U+AC1C>|language=korean|date=January 2, 2012|accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>

===2012: International promotions, TaeTiSeo and ''Girls & Peace''===
On January 12, 2012, the group attended the [[Golden Disk Awards]], held in [[Osaka]], bringing home two awards; the "Digital Bonsang" and the highly coveted "Digital Daesang". A week later, on January 19, 2012, they attended the [[Seoul Music Awards]], and brought back two awards, the "Bonsang" and "Popularity" awards. The group also won two awards from the [[Gaon Chart K-Pop Awards]], winning the Album Of The Year for the fourth Quarter and Oricon "Hallyu Singer" award.
[[File:SNSD at LG Cinema 3D World Festival (4).jpg|thumbnail|Girls' Generation perform "The Boys" at the LG Cinema 3D World Festival, April 1, 2012.]]

Their appearances on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' and ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael|Live! with Kelly]]'' on January 31, 2012, and February 1, 2012, where they performed remixes of the English version of "The Boys", marked the first time that a Korean musical act has performed on each of the shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtviggy.com/blog-posts/snsd-hits-us-media-bullseye-with-letterman-and-live-with-kelly-appearances/|title=SNSD Hits US Media Bullseye with "Letterman" and "Live With Kelly" Appearances|date=January 31, 2012|accessdate=November 15, 2012|author=Samantha Edussuriya|publisher=mtviggy.com}}</ref>

They also performed on the [[France|French]] show, ''[[Le Grand Journal (Canal+)|Le Grand Journal]]'', on February 9, 2012, after it was announced that they were to release "The Boys" on February 13, 2012, through [[Universal Music Group]]<U+2019>s [[Polydor Records]] in France. In the same month, Girls' Generation again topped [[Forbes]]'s [[Korea Power Celebrity 40]] list.<ref>[http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=025&aid=0002187244 <U+97D3><U+C720><U+BA85><U+C778> 40<U+BA85><U+C5D0> <U+C7AC><U+ACC4><U+C778><U+C0AC>'0'<U+2026>1<U+C704><U+B294> <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> :: <U+B124><U+C774><U+BC84> <U+B274><U+C2A4><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Figures for the groups total earnings for 2011 were released in March 2012. The group placed first among their label, earning over 100 billion won, or, approximately, $88.56 million USD.<ref name="<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C9C0><U+B09C><U+D574><U+B9CC> 200<U+C5B5> 3<U+B144> <U+B9E4><U+CD9C> 700<U+C5B5> <U+D6CC><U+CA4D>">{{cite web|url=http://star.mk.co.kr/new/view.php?mc=ST&no=172022&year=2012|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C9C0><U+B09C><U+D574><U+B9CC> 200<U+C5B5> 3<U+B144> <U+B9E4><U+CD9C> 700<U+C5B5> <U+D6CC><U+CA4D>|language=korean|publisher=star.mk.co.kr|date=March 17, 2012|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> Similarly, with their Japanese releases in 2012, the group ranked seventh among Japanese artists and as the top Korean artist in Japan in terms of monetary profit after generating over 4.3 billion Yen (US$51 million) in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enews24.interest.me/news/10/4150001_1601.html|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+65E5> <U+C624><U+B9AC><U+CF58> <U+C5F0><U+AC04><U+B9E4><U+CD9C> '550<U+C5B5>' <U+C885><U+D569> 7<U+C704><U+00B7><U+D55C><U+AD6D><U+AC00><U+C218> 1<U+C704>|language=Korean|publisher=enews24.interest.me|date=December 20, 2012|accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref>

April 2012 saw the formation of [[Girls' Generation-TTS]], or simply "TaeTiSeo", a subunit composed of members Taeyeon, Tiffany, and Seohyun. The subgroup released their first mini-album, ''[[Twinkle (EP)|Twinkle]]'', on May 2.<ref>[http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201204200100142240012588&servicedate=20120419 <U+C2A4><U+D3EC><U+CE20><U+C870><U+C120> :: <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+CCAB><U+BC88><U+C9F8> <U+C720><U+B2DB> '<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>-<U+D0DC><U+D2F0><U+C11C>' <U+D0C4><U+C0DD>. <U+BA64><U+BC84> <U+AD6C><U+C131><U+C740>?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> "Twinkle" debuted at number 126 on the [[Billboard 200]], selling over 3,000 copies and making it the highest charting K-Pop album on the chart thus far.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ho|first=Stewart|title=Taetiseo Debuts on Billboard 200 Chart and Achieves Highest Showing of a Korean Album|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=6239|accessdate=March 8, 2013|newspaper=News World|date=May 4, 2012}}</ref> On May 20, 2012, the group performed with their label-mates at the [[Honda Center]] in [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]], as part of the first date of [[SMTown Live World Tour III]]. The tour will continued to Tokyo, South Korea, Singapore, Thailand and Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite news|title=SM Entertainment artists to hold concert in Los Angeles on May 20|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2012040314283067243|publisher=asiae.co.kr|accessdate=April 25, 2012|newspaper=Asiae|date=April 3, 2012}}</ref>

"[[Paparazzi (Girls' Generation song)|Paparazzi]]" was released on June 27, 2012, serving as the lead single from their second Japanese-language album.<ref>[http://www.allkpop.com/2012/06/girls-generation-releases-album-details-track-list-for-paparazzi Girls' Generation releases details + track list for "Paparazzi"]</ref> "Paparazzi"'s release boosted the group's total single sales in the country to over 647,000, according to SoundScan Japan.<ref name="Jeff Benjamin">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/481799/girls-generation-push-japanese-domination-with-paparazzi-1-million-albums-sold|title=Girls' Generation Push Japanese Domination With 'Paparazzi,' 1 Million Albums Sold Read more at http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/481799/girls-generation-push-japanese-domination-with-paparazzi-1-million-albums-sold|publisher=billboard.com|author=Jeff Benjamin|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/481799/girls-generation-push-japanese-domination-with-paparazzi-1-million-albums-sold Girls' Generation Push Japanese Domination With 'Paparazzi,' 1 Million Albums Sold | Billboard<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> That same month, the group won "Best Album of the Year" for their debut Japanese album at the [[2012 MTV Video Music Awards Japan|2012 VMAJs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://my.entertainment.yahoo.com/news/2ne1-2pm-snsd-won-mtv-vma-japan-094000561.html|title=2NE1, 2PM and SNSD won MTV VMA Japan|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=July 22, 2012|publisher=my.entertainment.yahoo.com|author=Syahida Kamarudin}}</ref> It was announced on July 3, 2012, that the group was to release official stamps the following month, commemorating their 5th Anniversary. A total of 14 stamps were produced, which included autographed album covers. This marked the first time a celebrity had made a contract with [[Korea Post]] to produce stamps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201207030932_8950&category=All&query=Girls<U+2032>%20Generation%20(SNSD)&page=6|publisher=global.mnet.com|author=Stewart Ho|date=July 3, 2012|accessdate=August 27, 2012|title=[K-pop] SNSD Becomes First Korean Celebrity on Official Stamps}}</ref> Within an hour of the stamps' issuing, over half of the available stamp sheets had already sold out.<ref name="Stewart Ho 1">{{cite web|url=http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201208091328_11989&category=All&query=Girls<U+2032>%20Generation%20(SNSD)&page=1|title=[Issue] Half of Available SNSD Stamps Sell Out in First Hour of Release|date=August 9, 2012|accessdate=August 27, 2012|publisher=global.mnet.com|author=Stewart Ho}}</ref> On August 10, 2012, it was revealed that the group was to release a Blu-ray/DVD videography entitled "[[Girls' Generation Complete Video Collection]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=(Japanese) <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3000><U+30CB><U+30E5><U+30FC><U+30B7><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+FF06><U+6620><U+50CF><U+4F5C><U+54C1><U+96C6><U+3000>9/26<U+540C><U+6642><U+767A><U+58F2><U+6C7A><U+5B9A><U+FF01>|url=http://www.universal-music.co.jp/girlsgeneration/news/2012/08/10/|publisher=Universal Music|accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref>

"[[Oh! / All My Love Is For You]]", the group's second double A-side single was released on September 26, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/jp/album/oh!-single/id559951010|title="Oh!" <U+2014> Single by Girls' Generation|language=Japanese|work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]] JP|publisher=[[Apple Inc|Apple]]|accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> The release earned first place on Oricon<U+2019>s Weekly Single chart, selling 66,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite news|title=<U+3010><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+3011><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001><U+5973><U+6027><U+521D><U+306E><U+540C><U+6642>3<U+51A0><U+3000><U+65E5><U+672C><U+30C7><U+30D3><U+30E5><U+30FC>2<U+5E74><U+3067><U+30B7><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+521D><U+9996><U+4F4D>(Japanese)|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2017311/full/|accessdate=November 29, 2013|newspaper=Oricon}}</ref> The group's second Japanese album, ''[[Girls' Generation II: Girls & Peace]]'', was released on November 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.jp/<U+30BF><U+30A4><U+30C8><U+30EB><U+672A><U+5B9A>-<U+8C6A><U+83EF><U+521D><U+56DE><U+9650><U+5B9A><U+76E4>-DVD<U+4ED8>-<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3>/dp/B009K8JXPG/ref=sr_1_1?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1349139897&sr=1-1|title=<U+30BF><U+30A4><U+30C8><U+30EB><U+672A><U+5B9A>(<U+8C6A><U+83EF><U+521D><U+56DE><U+9650><U+5B9A><U+76E4>)(DVD<U+4ED8>) [CD+DVD]|language=Japanese|publisher=amazon.co.jp|date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref> The album was preceded by the single "[[Flower Power (song)|Flower Power]]", which was released on November 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.jp/FLOWER-POWER-<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3>/dp/B009K8JSX8/ref=sr_1_4?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1349139897&sr=1-4|title=FLOWER POWER [Maxi]|publisher=amazon.co.jp|date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref> "Flower Power" sold 29,000 copies in its first week, peaking at number five on the Oricon Chart. "Girls' Generation II: Girls & Peace" sold 116,963 copies in its first week of release, ranking third on Oricon's Weekly Albums Chart. "Girls & Peace" has since been certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] (RIAJ).<ref name="<U+4E00><U+822C><U+793E><U+56E3><U+6CD5><U+4EBA> <U+65E5><U+672C><U+30EC><U+30B3><U+30FC><U+30C9><U+5354><U+4F1A><U+FF5C><U+5404><U+7A2E><U+7D71><U+8A08>">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/gold/201211.html|title=<U+4E00><U+822C><U+793E><U+56E3><U+6CD5><U+4EBA> <U+65E5><U+672C><U+30EC><U+30B3><U+30FC><U+30C9><U+5354><U+4F1A><U+FF5C><U+5404><U+7A2E><U+7D71><U+8A08>|language=Japanese | publisher=[[RIAJ]]|accessdate=December 9, 2012|date=December 9, 2012}}</ref> The group released the [[2011 Girls' Generation Tour DVD]] on November 30, 2012, which featured footage from the 2011 concert tour of the same name.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}

The group released the track "[[Dancing Queen (Girls' Generation song)|Dancing Queen]]", a remake version of [[Mercy (Duffy song)|Duffy's Mercy]], on December 21, 2012.<ref name="starnews">{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2012122109364129503&type=3|title=<U+C18C><U+C2DC>, <U+CEF4><U+BC31> <U+C2E0><U+ACE1><U+C740> <U+82F1><U+AC00><U+C218> <U+B354><U+D53C> 'Mercy' <U+B9AC><U+BA54><U+C774><U+D06C>|date=December 21, 2012|accessdate=December 21, 2012|publisher=star.mt.co.kr|language=Korean}}</ref>

===2013: ''I Got a Boy'', touring and ''Love & Peace''===
[[File:Girls Generation in Jakarta.jpg|left|thumb|Girls' Generation during "Girls & Peace" World Tour Live in Jakarta.]]
On January 1, 2013, Girls' Generation released their fourth Korean-language album, ''[[I Got a Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.aladin.co.kr/shop/wproduct.aspx?ISBN=9314512630|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+2013> <U+C815><U+ADDC> 4<U+C9D1> I Got a Boy [10<U+C885> <U+C911> <U+B79C><U+B364>]|accessdate=December 21, 2012|date=January 1, 2013|publisher=music.aladin.co.kr|language=Korean}}</ref> The album sold over 265,000 copies in January, debuting atop the January [[Gaon Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon/ |title=Girls' Generation's "The Boys" album sales figure |date=January 7, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6EjIuxMIx |archivedate=February 26, 2013 |accessdate=February 26, 2013 |language=Korean |quote=select '<U+C6D4><U+AC04>' to find the monthly chart}}</ref> As well as charting on many ''Billboard'' album charts, including the number-one spot on the World Album chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard World Albums Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-01-19/world-albums{{!}}|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> The group began promotional appearances on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s [[M! Countdown]] and continued on into the start of February.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bntnews.hankyung.com/apps/news?popup=0&nid=04&c1=04&c2=04&c3=00&nkey=201301021327373&mode=sub_view |title=<U+2018><U+BC40><U+B760> <U+C2A4><U+D0C0><U+2019> <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+D6A8><U+C5F0><U+00B7><U+C720><U+B9AC>, <U+2018><U+C5E0><U+CE74><U+2019> <U+C2A4><U+D398><U+C15C> MC <U+B098><U+C120><U+B2E4> |publisher=bntnews.com |date=January 2, 2013 |accessdate=January 3, 2013 |language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109518707 |title=MBC <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300> <U+CEF4><U+BC31><U+C1FC>, 80<U+BD84> <U+D30C><U+ACA9><U+D3B8><U+C131> '<U+B300><U+D2B9><U+C9D1>' |publisher=osen.mt.co.kr |language=Korean |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref> The group also performed it on their MBC comeback special; ''[[Girls' Generation's Romantic Fantasy]]'' on January 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=MBC airs Girls Generation comeback special program 'Romantic Fantasy'|url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/mbc-airs-girls-generation-comeback-special-program-romantic-092900128.html|accessdate=November 29, 2013|newspaper=Yahoo|date=January 2, 2013}}</ref> The group also performed on [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] Hope Concert.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} Girls' Generation held an hour-long "Virtual Concert" broadcast live via Naver Music on January 5, 2013 where they perform "I Got a Boy", "Talk Talk" and "Dancing Queen".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20130105n10140|title=[T<U+D3EC><U+D1A0> l <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>] '<U+AD6D><U+BBFC> <U+AC78><U+ADF8><U+B8F9><U+C758> <U+C778><U+AE30>'(V <U+CF58><U+C11C><U+D2B8>)|date=January 5, 2013|accessdate=January 6, 2013|publisher=news.nate.com|language=Korean}}</ref>

Girls' Generation embarked on their [[Girls & Peace: 2nd Japan Tour]] in [[Kobe]] on February 9, 2013 and continued for a total of 20 shows across seven cities. The tour was attended by over 200,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/76597 |title=<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+300C>Oh!<U+300D><U+65E5><U+672C><U+7248><U+30D3><U+30B8><U+30E5><U+30A2><U+30EB><U+516C><U+958B><U+FF06><U+30A2><U+30EA><U+30FC><U+30CA><U+30C4><U+30A2><U+30FC>|date=September 15, 2012|accessdate=December 3, 2012|publisher=natalie.mu|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>[http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2013042208394973876&type=3 <U+C18C><U+C2DC>, <U+B450><U+BC88><U+C9F8> <U+65E5><U+D22C><U+C5B4> 20<U+B9CC> <U+B3D9><U+C6D0>..<U+97D3><U+AC78><U+ADF8><U+B8F9> <U+CD5C><U+B2E4> - <U+C2A4><U+D0C0><U+B274><U+C2A4><!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The group released their first Japanese remix entitled, ''[[Best Selection Non Stop Mix]]'' on March 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universal-music.co.jp/girlsgeneration/news/2013/02/05b/ |publisher=Universal Music Japan |language=Japanese |title=<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3> <U+521D><U+306E><U+30AA><U+30D5><U+30A3><U+30B7><U+30E3><U+30EB>MIX CD<U+767A><U+58F2><U+6C7A><U+5B9A>!! <U+2013> <U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3> <U+2013> GIRLS GENERATION <U+2013> UNIVERSAL MUSIC JAPAN |deadurl=no |accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> The album ranked number 6 on Oricon<U+2019>s weekly album chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2013-04-01/more/2/|title=CD Chart (April 2013)|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=September 13, 2013}}</ref>

On April 11, 2013, the group released their [[2011 Girls' Generation Tour (album)|2011 Girls' Generation Tour]] live album. The album features the July 23 and 24, 2011 Girls' Generation's concerts in [[Seoul]] at the [[Olympic Gymnastics Arena]] for their [[2011 Girls' Generation Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joynews.inews24.com/php/news_view.php?g_menu=700300&g_serial=735943|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+CF58><U+C11C><U+D2B8> <U+C2E4><U+D669> <U+B2F4><U+C740> <U+B77C><U+C774><U+BE0C> <U+C568><U+BC94> <U+BC1C><U+B9E4>|date=April 5, 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2013|publisher=joynews.com|language=Korean}}</ref> On April 26, 2013, Girls' Generation announced their first world tour ''[[Girls' Generation World Tour Girls & Peace]]'' with the first dates in Seoul on June 8 and 9, 2013.<ref name="chosunsports">{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201304270100212130016566&servicedate=20130426|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+B4DC><U+B514><U+C5B4> <U+C6D4><U+B4DC><U+D22C><U+C5B4> <U+B098><U+C120><U+B2E4>. 6<U+C6D4> 8, 9<U+C77C><U+C5D0><U+B294> <U+C11C><U+C6B8><U+C11C> 2<U+B144> <U+B9CC><U+C5D0> <U+B2E8><U+B3C5> <U+CF58><U+C11C> <U+D2B8>|publisher=sports.chosun.com|date=April 26, 2013|accessdate=April 26, 2013|language=Korean}}</ref>

The group released their seventh Japanese single, "[[Love & Girls]]" on June 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finn-neo.com/user.cgi?articleid=7089&actmode=NewsArticleList&fanclub_id=2#article_7089|title=<U+30B7><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+300C>LOVE&GIRLS<U+300D><U+521D><U+56DE><U+9650><U+5B9A><U+76E4><U+306B><U+300C>LOVE&GIRLS<U+300D><U+306E>MUSIC VIDEO<U+304C><U+53CE><U+9332><U+6C7A><U+5B9A><U+FF01>|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 16, 2013|publisher=SONE Japan|language=Japanese}}</ref> According to the Oricon Daily Chart, "Love & Girls" rose from rank number 6 to number 4 the day after it debuted on the chart.<ref>{{cite news|title=SNSD<U+2032>s <U+2032>Love & Girls<U+2032> Rises Two Ranks to Arrive at No. 4 on Oricon|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/39071|accessdate=August 14, 2013|newspaper=Mwave|date=June 21, 2013}}</ref> The single was able to sold 42,796 physical copies on its first week and took the no. 4 spot in Oricon Weekly Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=<U+306E>CD<U+30B7><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+9031><U+9593><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0>|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2013-07-01/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref>

Girls' Generation released their eighth Japanese single, "[[Galaxy Supernova]]" on September 18, 2013 along with [[Girls & Peace: 2nd Japan Tour#DVD|Girls' Generation -Girls & Peace- Japan 2nd Tour]] DVD and Blu-ray.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} According to [[Oricon]], the single achieved the number 1 spot on the day of release on Oricon Daily Single<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/d/2013-09-18/ | title=Oricon Daily Single Chart (18 September) | work=Oricon | accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> while ''Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s Girls & Peace: 2nd Japan Tour'' took the no.1 spot on September 18<U+2019>s Oricon Daily DVD Chart.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/dg/d/2013-09-17/ | title=DVD, Blu-ray Chart | work=Oricon | accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> After one week of release, Galaxy Supernova managed to sold 50,793 physical copies while the DVD and Blu-ray sold a total of 53,256 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oricon Weekly, 9/16-9/22|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2013-09-30/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=<U+3010><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+3011><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001>3<U+4F5C><U+76EE><U+306E>DVD<U+7DCF><U+5408><U+9996><U+4F4D><U+3000><U+6D77><U+5916><U+5973><U+6027><U+6B74><U+4EE3>1<U+4F4D><U+30BF><U+30A4>|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/music/2028995/full/|accessdate=September 25, 2013|newspaper=Oricon}}</ref>

Girls Generation came up big at the inaugural [[YouTube Music Awards]] by snagging Best Music Video and beating popular acts such as [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Psy]], [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Justin Bieber]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nihongogo.com/2013/11/girls-generation-comes-up-big-at-the-youtube-music-awards/ | title=Girls Generation Comes Up Big at the YouTube Music Awards | publisher=Nihongogo | date=November 4, 2013 | accessdate=November 6, 2013}}</ref> The group released their ninth Japanese single, "[[My Oh My (Girls' Generation song)|My Oh My]]" on November 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/11/girls-generation-reveals-catchy-japanese-single-my-oh-my#axzz2jbW7MV8i | title=Girls' Generation reveals catchy Japanese single 'My Oh My'  | publisher=allkpop | date=November 4, 2013 | accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>

The group released their seventh studio album, "[[Love & Peace (Girls' Generation album)|Love & Peace]]" on December 11, 2013 after the release of "[[Love & Girls]]", "[[Galaxy Supernova]]" and "[[My Oh My (Girls' Generation song)|My Oh My]]" in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.universal-music.co.jp/girlsgeneration/news/2013/11/21/ | title=<U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3> <U+5F85><U+671B><U+306E>3rd<U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+306E><U+30BF><U+30A4><U+30C8><U+30EB><U+30FB><U+30C8><U+30E9><U+30C3><U+30AF><U+30EA><U+30B9><U+30C8><U+304C><U+9042><U+306B><U+89E3><U+7981><U+FF01> | work=[[Universal Music Group|Universal Music Japan]] | publisher=[[Universal Music Group|Universal Music]] | language=Japanese | date=November 21, 2013}}</ref> The album manage to debut at number-one spot on Oricon's Daily album charts after selling more than 37,386 copies.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/d/2013-12-10/ | title=CD<U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+30C7><U+30A4><U+30EA><U+30FC><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0> | trans_title=CD Album Daily Ranking | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Lmqmovle | archivedate=December 11, 2013 | publisher=[[Oricon]] | date=December 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref>  After the first week, with sales amounting to about 129,000, it debuted on the weekly ''Oricon'' chart at number one.<ref>{{cite news|title="CD<U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+9031><U+9593><U+30E9><U+30F3><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0>" [CD Album weekly ranking] (in Japanese)|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2013-12-23/|accessdate=December 19, 2013|newspaper=Oricon}}</ref> Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s self-titled debut Japanese album, released in June 2011, also ranked first in the weekly album chart, making Girls<U+2019> Generation the first Korean girl group to have two albums place first on a weekly album ranking, surpassing [[Kara (band)|Kara]].<ref>{{cite news|title=<U+3010><U+30AA><U+30EA><U+30B3><U+30F3><U+3011><U+5C11><U+5973><U+6642><U+4EE3><U+3001>2<U+5E74><U+534A><U+3076><U+308A><U+306B><U+30A2><U+30EB><U+30D0><U+30E0><U+9996><U+4F4D><U+3000><U+97D3><U+56FD><U+5973><U+6027><U+30B0><U+30EB><U+30FC><U+30D7><U+6700><U+591A>2<U+4F5C><U+76EE>|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2032043/full/|accessdate=December 19, 2013|newspaper=Oricon|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>

S.M. Entertainment announced that Girls Generation will perform for the first ever "[[SM Town Week]]"  on December 22, 2013. Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s December 22 solo concert will be called, <U+201C>SMTOWN WEEK GIRLS<U+2019> GENERATION <U+2013> Marchen Fantasy<U+201D>. The concert will have a fairytale-like visual theme, with lots of different stages and showy video effects.<ref>{{cite news|title="SM <U+C704><U+D06C> <U+D2B9><U+BCC4> <U+ACF5><U+C5F0>"<U+2026><U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, 12<U+C6D4> <U+B2E8><U+B3C5> <U+CF58><U+C11C><U+D2B8>(Korean)|url=http://www.dispatch.co.kr/r.dp?idx=21995|accessdate=November 29, 2013|newspaper=Dispatch|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref>

===2014: ''Mr.Mr.''===
[[File:KOCIS Korea Mnet Girls Generation 05 (12987267134).jpg|thumb|250px|Girls' Generation in 2014 at ''[[M! Countdown]]'']]
On February 10, 2014, S.M. Entertainment released the album name, the release date as well as the video teaser on their YouTube channel for ''[[Mr.Mr. (EP)|Mr.Mr.]]'' and stated that the song would be released on February 19 to various online music portal sites, while the actual album will only be released on February 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1uw5gudgWQA|title=Girls' Generation <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>_'Mr.Mr.'_Image Teaser|work=SMTOWN|publisher=YouTube|date=February 10, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014|last=|first=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://now.smtown.com/#/543|title=SMTOWN NOW|work=SMTOWN|publisher=S. M. Entertainment|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014|last=|first=}}</ref>

Things took a turn when an exclusive report by OSEN revealed that during the editing process for Girls' Generation's music video on the 13th, a loss of data occurred resulting in a deletion of a portion of the footage. Girls' Generation originally planned to release their title track and music video on the 19th and kick off their comeback stage on 'M! Countdown' on the 20th ahead of their album release on the 24th. However, if a re-filming is required to accommodate for the loss of data, insiders are saying that there is a possibility that Girls' Generation's comeback or MV release date may be pushed back by up to two weeks to allow for the filming and re-editing. <ref>{{cite news|title=[<U+B2E8><U+B3C5>] <U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+BBA4><U+BE44> <U+B370><U+C774><U+D130> <U+D30C><U+C190> <U+C0AC><U+ACE0> <U+BC1C><U+C0DD>..'<U+CEF4><U+BC31> <U+BE44><U+C0C1>'|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109783576|accessdate=February 14, 2014|newspaper=Osen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Girls' Generation confirms comeback date with 1st teaser for 'Mr.Mr'!|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/02/girls-generation-confirms-comeback-date-with-1st-teaser-for-mrmr#axzz2tPluqSOK|publisher=allkpop|accessdate=February 10, 2014|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Girls' Generation's upcoming music video runs into a mishap, may possibly cause delays|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/02/girls-generations-upcoming-music-video-runs-into-a-mishap-may-possibly-cause-delays#axzz2tPluqSOK|publisher=allkpop|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Insiders say 2NE1 may be going up against Girls' Generation this month with album release|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/02/insiders-say-2ne1-may-be-going-up-against-girls-generation-this-month-with-album-release#axzz2tPluqSOK|date=February 12, 2014|author=allkpop}}</ref>

Girls' Generation released ''Mr.Mr'' on February 24 to various Korean and overseas music sites, including [[iTunes Store|iTunes]],.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://itunes.apple.com/album/girls-generation-4th-mini/id826334410|title=Girls' Generation 4th Mini Album 'Mr. Mr.' - EP|date=February 23, 2014|author=iTunes}}</ref> The physical copy of the album was released on February 27, 2014. The group is scheduled on March 6 episode of Mnet's M!Countdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ph.celebrity.yahoo.com/news/snsd-to-unveil-mr-mr-today-2-24-051512543.html|title=SNSD to Unveil <U+2018>Mr.Mr<U+2019> Today (2/24) at 5PM|date=February 23, 2014|author=Yahoo Philippines}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/yonhap-news-agency/140224/girls-generation-unveils-new-album-itunes|title=Girls' Generation unveils new album on iTunes|date=February 24, 2014|author=Global Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=<U+C18C><U+B140><U+C2DC><U+B300>, <U+C624><U+B298> <U+AE30><U+C2B5> <U+CEF4><U+BC31>.."<U+C624><U+D6C4> 5<U+C2DC> 'Mr.Mr.' <U+BC1C><U+D45C>"|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109792094|accessdate=24 February 2014|newspaper=Osen|date=24 February 2014}}</ref>

It was revealed that Girls' Generation will headline [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] 2014 in Los Angeles. [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] will take place over two days, August 9th and August 10th, with artists split between the two days of performances.<ref>[http://www.soshified.com/2014/05/girls-generation-to-perform-at-kcon-2014 Girls<U+2019> Generation to Perform at <U+2018>KCON 2014<U+2032> in Los Angeles]</ref>

In June, Time magazine listed "Mr. Mr." as one of the top 25 best songs so far for the year.<ref>[http://time.com/2801365/best-songs-of-2014-so-far Here Are the 25 Best Songs of 2014 (So Far)] Time.com (June 2, 2014). Retrieved on June 24, 2014.</ref>

Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s  will release [[Best of Girls' Generation|The Best]] album in Japan on July 23rd. The album will include the group<U+2019>s hit tracks and new songs, as well as behind-the-scenes videos with footage starting from Girls<U+2019> Generation<U+2019>s debut in Japan in 2010.

